data.name: xrLabel105.Text
data.value: The DUTY Rates for products entering the UK are set and controlled by HM Revenue & Customs. DUTY Rates should be the same no matter which EU country you are importing your product into but may differ depending from where the goods are being sent i.e. the origin. The DUTY Rates are set by the EU and run the full length of the calendar year from 1st January to 31st December and can be found as the published rates on the HM Revenue & Customs Website. DUTY Rates average out at 5-9% but in some cases can be 0% and in higher cases can be up as high as 85%.

data.name: xrLabel102.Text
data.value: Courier and Customs Solutions Limited cannot include these charges in the cost of the shipping due to each country having thousands of different tariffs and each Customs authority in each country using a different rate to calculate the DUTY. This is all based on how many pieces of that product are included within the shipment and the cost of sending it from A and to B. The calculation of this is based on the information provided on the Customs paperwork, in particular the contents, declared value and weight.

data.name: xrLabel98.Text
data.value: VAT is a sales tax levied on the sale of goods and services by VAT registered businesses throughout the UK. In cases where you are choosing to import goods from overseas, these are still liable for VAT when they come through the port of entry. This way it prevents you getting an unfair advantage on buying goods from overseas instead of buying them within the EU.

data.name: xrLabel83.Text
data.value:
An amount of £11 or 2.5% of the total DUTY and/or VAT incurred, whichever is the greater. This charge for private individuals may be rounded down to the nearest round pound amount.
If the total DUTY and/or VAT incurred are less than £300 then a flat amount of £11 will be incurred as this is less than 2.5%.
For example: If the total DUTY and/or VAT amount equals £145, then £9.50 would be charged.
The 2.5% will be incurred if the total DUTY and/or VAT are greater than £300. For example, if the total DUTY and/or VAT amount equals £567.00 then an amount of 2.5% will apply i.e. £14.18.

data.name: xrLabel85.Text
data.value: There are several occasions when DUTY AND VAT may not be liable to be paid: - The value of the Product/ Goods is £15 or less but this does not include the value of postage, packing and other miscellaneous costs.

data.name: xrLabel95.Text
data.value: Customs DUTY is a tax charged on all goods that are produced and purchased from outside the UK & EU. This is controlled by HM Revenue & Customs and not by Courier and Customs Solutions Limited. The purpose of the DUTY is to keep the prices fair and the competition equal for the cost of making the goods inside and outside the UK & EU. Once the goods have passed through the borders of the UK the goods are now what is deemed into ‘free circulation’ and are allowed to move throughout the EU without any further restrictions or need to pay DUTY.

data.name: xrLabel67.Text
data.value: With the boom in eCommerce shopping online becomes more and more common. You may log onto a shop located the other side of the world to make your purchase as opposed to walking down your local high street. The issue with this, and what is often not understood, is when the products enter the country they are liable to DUTY AND VAT payments. This often comes as a surprise to many people so we have made a simple how to guide to walk you through the process: Making importing as simple as 1,2,3.

data.name: xrLabel71.Text
data.value: All goods that are not from either the UK or EU are, in most cases, liable for Customs DUTY AND VAT on entry into the United Kingdom. As all the goods pass through the border they must be declared to HM Revenue and Customs. This includes goods bought over the Internet.

data.name: xrLabel73.Text
data.value: What often catches many people out is even if someone has sent you a gift you could still be liable to DUTY AND VAT. If that gift has been sent from a country overseas that is outside the UK and the EU and is valued over GBP 34, you would also be in line to pay the DUTY AND VAT. Unless the kind person who has sent you this gift has agreed to pay it!

data.name: xrLabel75.Text
data.value: This could be your first time of hearing about our company, Courier and Customs Solutions Limited, and you have received an invoice from us requesting payment via an online payment gateway or bank transfer. So, quite rightly, you may have some questions you would like answered before you are comfortable to pay it. This could be an unexpected bill and you may be unsure what it is or how it is calculated.

data.name: xrLabel76.Text
data.value: These DUTY AND VAT rates are set and levied by HM Revenue & Customs. All Courier and Customs Solutions Limited. is doing is paying these on your behalf first and then eclaiming them back before we can release your shipment from our warehouse and send it on its way for local delivery.

data.name: xrLabel79.Text
data.value: The receiver of the shipment is legally responsible for paying for the DUTY AND VAT of the shipment, unless the shipper of the product has selected a Delivered Duty Paid (DDP) option at the time of shipment.This would have had to have been agreed upon on the airway bill before the shipment was picked up by Courier and Customs Solutions Limited. Even private individuals and households that have logged online to make purchases from all around the world are liable to pay these duties and taxes, so please be very careful when onducting your online shopping that you know who is liable to pay the DUTY AND VAT. In many cases the price you will see online will not include the DUTY AND VAT that HM Revenue & Customs will charge upon entry into the UK and you, as the receiver, would be expected to pay.

data.name: xrLabel81.Text
data.value: Courier and Customs Solutions Limited is not able to release your consignments from our warehouse until we have got the payment in our account for the DUTY AND VAT that we would have paid out on your behalf. As most private individuals and households do not have a deferment account, Courier and Customs Solutions Limited pre pays this amount for you and then re bills it back. This is the reason why we cannot release the goods before we have received the payment. In order for us to provide this service we levy a Disbursement Handling Fee that will be added to the invoice for clearing the shipment through Customs and getting it ready to be out for the final delivery.
